05023nam a22006015i 9780822385820DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223858207 a10.1515/97808223858202doi  a(DE-B1597)554002  a(OCoLC)1153030574  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHT1523b.W45 2004 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aWeinbaum, Alys Eve, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWayward Reproductions :bGenealogies of Race and Nation in Transatlantic Modern Thought /cAlys Eve Weinbaum; Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan, Inderpal Grewal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b3 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One Genealogy Unbound: Reproduction and Contestation of the Racial Nation -- tChapter Two Writing Feminist Genealogy: Charlotte Perkins Gilman and the Reproduction of Racial Nationalism -- tChapter Three Engels's Originary Ruse: Race and Reproduction in the Story of Capital -- tChapter Four Sexual Selection and the Birth of Psychoanalysis: Darwin, Freud, and the Universalization of Wayward Reproduction -- tChapter Five The Sexual Politics of Black Internationalism: W. E. B. Du Bois and the Reproduction of Racial Globality -- tCoda Gene/alogies for a New Millennium -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWayward Reproductions breaks apart and transfigures prevailing understandings of the interconnection among ideologies of racism, nationalism, and imperialism. Alys Eve Weinbaum demonstrates how these ideologies were founded in large part on what she calls "the race/reproduction bind"--the notion that race is something that is biologically reproduced. In revealing the centrality of ideas about women's reproductive capacity to modernity's intellectual foundations, Weinbaum highlights the role that these ideas have played in naturalizing oppression. She argues that attention to how the race/reproduction bind is perpetuated across national and disciplinary boundaries is a necessary part of efforts to combat racism.Gracefully traversing a wide range of discourses--including literature, evolutionary theory, early anthropology, Marxism, feminism, and psychoanalysis--Weinbaum traces a genealogy of the race/reproduction bind within key intellectual formations of the late nineteenth and twentieth centuries. She examines two major theorists of genealogical thinking-Friedrich Nietzsche and Michel Foucault-and unearths the unacknowledged ways their formulations link race and reproduction. She explores notions of kinship and the replication of racial difference that run through Charlotte Perkins Gilman's work; Marxist thinking based on Friedrich Engel's The Origin of the Family; Charles Darwin's theory of sexual selection; and Sigmund Freud's early studies on hysteria. She also describes W. E. B. Du Bois's efforts to transcend ideas about the reproduction of race that underwrite citizenship and belonging within the United States. In a coda, Weinbaum brings the foregoing analysis to bear on recent genomic and biotechnological innovations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aGenealogy (Philosophy). 0aHuman reproductionxSocial aspects. 0aRace awarenessxHistory. 0aRacexPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aGrewal, Inderpal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle 